Q4.(d)

H0 - Avg profit by the new customers is less than or equal to that of old customers H1 - Avg profit by the new customers is more than that of old customers

new  = ads[ads$newcustomer == "yes", ]$profit
old =  ads[ads$newcustomer == "no", ]$profit
  
# Assuming equal population variances
t.test(new, old, paired=F, var.equal=T, alternative="greater", conf.level=0.95)

##  Two Sample t-test

As p value > 0.05 (aplha), we fail to reject the null hypothesis saying that the avg profit by the new customers is less than or equal to that of old customers. Hence, we conlclude avg profit by the new customers is more than that of old customers.

P value > Alpha(0.05) We failed to reject the Null Hypothesis. Hence, we can conclude that the mean profit for each social media platform is the same.

Q.7

We are given $100 to spend on the advertisement. In general, an ad is more effective only when the user comes across it multiple times. In that way it stays in the users mind which gives us an edge when the user makes a purchasing decision. Additionally, $100 is not a huge amount to be distributed into multiple targeted segments. Hence, we would spend the entire amount into a single targeted group of users.

Looking at the distributions and medians for each attribute, socialmedia and agegroup show the maximum variation of median among its values. With Twitter having the maximum median in socialmedia, we cannot be sure because of the low amount of data we have for twitter. Next, the median values for TikTok and YouTube are almost in the similar range. We do not have a clear winner considering this scenario. In case of age groups, the 35-52 age bucket has the maximum median. This makes sense because that is generally an age where you are financially stable and have larger spending capacity. Hence, we will target the 35-52 age group.

We would target the old customers itself considering the $100 budget is too less to lure in new customer. This is also validated by the higher median of no value for the newcutomer attribute. Regarding the type of device, 76% of the data we have is for computer users and just 24% for mobile users. In the distribution as well, the median for computer users is higher. Hence, we will target the computer users. If we look at the medians, seasons does not have a huge impact over the profit %. However, if we have to pick one of them, the spring season is a good bet as it has larger range for quartile 3 & 4 and also a longer whisker towards the positive side. This will give us a higher probability of getting better results.

Ultimately, we would use the entire $100 amount to target ads to old customers of 35 to 52 age group using YouTube on their computers in the spring season.
